# KORD 2.2 - Complete beginner guide

This guide is written for people who have never used KORD before.
It takes you from first launch to daily usage with clear, practical steps.

---

## 1) What KORD is

KORD is a local music management and playback software.

With KORD you can:
- use your audio files stored on disk;
- organize library, metadata, covers, playlists, and queue;
- use download/import tools (Studio area);
- manage separate local accounts on the same server.

In short: player + library + maintenance tools.

---

## 2) Minimum requirements

You need:
- a music folder with audio files;
- KORD running (web or desktop app);
- internet (optional, but useful for metadata/covers/downloads).

If this is your first launch, your top priority is configuring the library folder.

---

## 3) First launch walkthrough

### Step 1 - Open Settings
Go to **Settings** from the main navigation.

### Step 2 - Configure Library
In the Library section:
- set the root path of your music folder (when allowed);
- save and reload.

KORD will index your files and build your library from there.

### Step 3 - Personalize UI
In Settings:
- choose language;
- choose theme;
- choose visualizer mode.

### Step 4 - Verify library content
Open **Library** and check artists/albums/tracks.
If nothing appears, use refresh/sync.

---

## 4) Main sections (what each does)

## Dashboard
- collection overview;
- quick access to listening, favorites, and quality alerts.

## Listen
- now playing track;
- upcoming queue;
- lyrics and recents.

## Library
- browse by artists, genres, moods;
- search and filters;
- quick actions on albums and tracks.

## Studio
- download/import;
- album/track metadata tools;
- cover management;
- advanced library utilities.

## Queue
- current playback order;
- reorder, remove, clear.

## Playlists
- create, rename, delete;
- save queue as playlist.

## Favorites / Recent
- liked tracks;
- listening history.

## Statistics
- top tracks/artists/albums/genres;
- usage summaries.

## Settings
- accounts, network, backup, library, UI preferences.

---

## 5) Start listening (quick flow)

1. Open **Library**.
2. Open an artist or album.
3. Press play on a track.
4. Use player controls (play/pause, next, previous, volume).

Tip: for continuous listening, use the queue instead of starting one track at a time.

---

## 6) Queue: recommended usage

The queue is the core of continuous playback.

You can:
- add tracks;
- move them up/down;
- remove items;
- clear all;
- save queue as a playlist.

Best practice:
- load an album or selected tracks first;
- reorder queue;
- save it as playlist if you want to reuse it.

---

## 7) Playlists: practical management

In **Playlists** you can:
- create new playlists;
- add current track;
- play full playlist;
- rename or delete playlists.

Best practice:
- one playlist per context (workout, focus, travel, relax);
- clear and consistent names.

---

## 8) Track metadata editing

Open "Edit track" from any track in Library.

Main fields:
- display title;
- release date;
- genres;
- moods;
- lyrics (separate dialog).

### Lyrics dialog
In **Edit lyrics** you can:
- paste/write lyrics manually;
- use **Auto LRC**;
- read fetch errors directly in the lyrics dialog.

### File deletion
The track dialog also includes file deletion.
Warning: this is irreversible.

---

## 9) Album metadata editing

The album dialog lets you update album-level data and improve metadata consistency.
Useful for imported libraries with mixed/uneven tags.

Benefits:
- cleaner search results;
- better sorting consistency;
- more uniform library.

---

## 10) Genres and moods (smart usage)

Moods significantly improve navigation and shuffle behavior.

Benefits:
- quick context-based filtering;
- better random/shuffle control;
- cross-artist discovery.

Tips:
- assign 1-3 moods to key tracks;
- keep genres simple and consistent.

---

## 11) Studio: full practical guide

### 11.1 Discover/Catalog
Choose which content to include in your current account view.
Very useful in multi-account scenarios.

### 11.2 Download
Download/import from links (depending on available modes).

Checklist:
- choose the correct destination folder;
- monitor operation logs;
- use dedup/replace options only when needed.

### 11.3 Metadata
You can:
- update album metadata;
- update track metadata;
- scan missing-only or full library;
- clean obsolete entries in `kord-trackinfo`;
- infer genres at scale.

Recommended flow for large libraries:
1. run missing-only scan first;
2. review results;
3. run full scan only if needed.

### 11.4 Covers
Search and save album covers.
If changes do not appear immediately, refresh the view.

### 11.5 Multi-account sharing
Share/link content between profiles while keeping favorites, queue, and user state separated.

---

## 12) Search and keyboard shortcuts

Use global search when you do not know where a track is.
Use artist/genre/mood filters when browsing.

Shortcuts:
- `/` or `Ctrl+K`: focus search;
- `Space`: play/pause;
- `I`: open Listen section.

---

## 13) Settings: what to configure

## Accounts
- create separate local profiles;
- each account keeps its own user state.

## Library
- configure music root;
- remote sessions may be read-only.

## UI
- language, theme, visualizer.

## Network
- API port and estimated LAN URL.

## External sharing (Cloudflare)
- in Settings > Network you can log into Cloudflare and start external sharing;
- when sharing is active, KORD shows a public HTTPS URL for access outside your LAN;
- with `trycloudflare` mode, the URL is temporary and may change after each restart;
- so if you restart the server/app, it is normal to get a different `https://...trycloudflare.com` link;
- for a permanent URL, use a named Cloudflare tunnel with your own domain (advanced setup).

## Download cookies
- YouTube cookies management on server side (if used).

## Backup/Restore
- backup settings and metadata (no audio files);
- restore from KORD zip backup.

## Activity log
- server activity history.

## Colophon and disclaimer
- legal and responsibility notes at the bottom of Settings.

---

## 14) Backup and safe operation

Best practices:
- run backups regularly;
- always backup before large edits;
- keep clean folder/album naming;
- test complex operations on a small subset first.

---

## 15) Common issues (quick fixes)

### I cannot see my music
- check library path in Settings;
- verify folder permissions;
- run refresh/sync.

### Metadata does not update
- verify internet (for online fetch);
- check Studio logs;
- try missing-only scan first.

### Auto LRC does not return lyrics
- open "Edit lyrics";
- run Auto LRC;
- read the error in the lyrics dialog;
- add manual lyrics if needed.

### Cover does not change
- verify destination album;
- save again;
- refresh library view.

### Download does not start
- check URL and selected mode;
- check destination folder;
- inspect detailed logs.

---

## 16) Recommended start-to-finish flow

1. configure library root;
2. index and verify content;
3. fix main metadata;
4. add missing covers;
5. assign moods to key tracks;
6. create base playlists;
7. enable backup routine.

This keeps your library clean, consistent, and easy to maintain.

